  "description": "<h2 id=\"introduction\">Introduction</h2>\n<p>A small tributary of Perham Creek located between Wygant Peak and\nMitchell Point. Not a major objective by any means, but /might/ be an\namusing diversion when other creeks are flowing at extreme levels.\nLittle Perham had a major water release in 2016 (natural dam upstream\ngiving way) that scoured the creek all the way down to the bedrock, but\nit wasn't nearly as interesting when we came back a year later. Do not\nexpect greatness. This is a bottom-of-the-barrel creek.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Beware poison oak throughout the area.</li>\n<li>The geology in this area seems fairly unstable. Beware landslides\nand loose rocks.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"approach\">Approach</h2>\n<p>Park at Mitchell Point. From the parking area, backtrack down the\nroad a short distance to find the gate signed for the \"Wyeth Trail\".\nFollow the trail west about a mile.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>En route you will pass the aforementioned two-tier 200ft falls set\nin a deep alcove on the left. This falls stems from a low-flow creek\nwhich only runs in the early season and might be a good one to combine\nwith Little Perham. Reaching the top of this falls requires significant\nbushwhacking. It is not known if this falls has been rappelled\npreviously. A small user trail leads to the base of the falls.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>About a quarter-mile further west, reach a trail junction. Turn left\non the old Chetwoot Trail up under a powerline for about 0.4mi until the\ntrail crosses the drainage of Little Perham. Head downstream 100yrds to\nthe top of R1.</p>\n<h2 id=\"descent\">Descent</h2>\n<p>Head downstream to the top of R1.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>R1: The falls is vertical for about 65ft, then the creek cascades\ndown a series of short drops and low-angle bedrock ramps. We climbed up\na steep embankment and anchored off a tree DCR. (Beware poison oak and\nuse caution approaching the tree as the slope was pretty loose.) Given\nthe geologically unsettled nature of the canyon in 2016, we deemed it\nbest to rappel right down the watercourse as the best means for avoiding\nrockfall. We ran out a 60m rope all the way to the end which was\nsuffficent to get down the main drop and about 2/3rds of the way down\nthe bedrock tiers. Pulling the rope was clean, and we were able to\ndownclimb the remainder to a large logjam at the very bottom. In higher\nflow, it might be better to break this up into several shorter rappels -\nalthough anchors may be tricky to come by in the drainage.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Below the falls, continue down-canyon. There are several downclimbs,\nbut no real difficulties. After 5min, reach confluence with Perham\nCreek.</p>\n<h2 id=\"exit\">Exit</h2>\n<p>Follow the Wygant Peak trail DCR back to your car.</p>\n<h2 id=\"red_tape\">Red tape</h2>\n<p>None.</p>\n<h2 id=\"beta_sites\">Beta sites</h2>\n<h2 id=\"trip_reports_and_media\">Trip reports and media</h2>\n<h2 id=\"background\">Background</h2>\n<p>Creek was probably first descended by Portland locals in 2016.</p>\n<p>Perham Creek sports at least one major waterfall (30ft) located at\nabout 600ft elevation on the creek - although reaching it was a\nbushwhack of epic proportions in 2016.</p>\n<h2 id=\"further_explorations\">Further Explorations</h2>\n<p>Just east of Little Perham is another drainage sporting a 200ft two\ntier low-flow falls. This drop could be combined with a venture to\nLittle Perham, but has not yet been explored.</p>\n",
